definition.value: An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of oscr#3.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of oscr#3-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy fatty acid ascaroside anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of oscr#7. The conjugate base of oscr#7 and the major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of oscr#7.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of oscr#7-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy fatty acid ascaroside anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of oscr#9. The conjugate base of oscr#9 and the major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of oscr#9
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of oscr#9-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An agonist at the transient receptor potential vanilloid 4 (TRPV4).
A dithiophosphatidylcholine that is sn-dithiophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl substituents at S-1 and S-2 are both heptanoyl.
A nitramine that is N,N-bis(2-hydroxypropyl)nitrosamine in which the nitroso group has undergone formal oxidation to the corresponding nitro group. A potent pancreatic carcinogen.
A monothioglycerol phosphate ester of a phosphocholine.
The dithioglycerol phosphate ester of a phosphocholine.
A monothioglycerophosphocholine that is an sn-1- or -2-monothioglycero-3-phosphocholine bearing one or two acyl substituents at positions 1 and/or 2.
A dithioglycerophosphocholine that is 1,2-dithioglycero-3-phosphocholine bearing two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2.
An sn-monothiophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl substituents at O-1 and S-2 are hexadecyl and arachidinoyl respectively.

An sn-monothiophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl substituents at O-1 and S-2 are hexadecyl and hetanoyl respectively; an analogue of diheptanoyl thio-PC that contains an ether-linked saturated C16 moiety at the sn-1 position rather than a heptanoyl thiol ester.

An sn-monothiophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl substituents at O-1 and S-2 are both palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl); a chromogenic  phospholipase A2 substrate that contains a palmitoyl thioester at the sn-2 position of the glycerol backbone.
An RNA fragment comprised of two guanosine, two adenosine and three cytidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence G-A-G-A-C-C-C.
An RNA fragment comprised of three guanosine, two adenosine and four cytidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence G-A-G-A-G-A-C-C-C-A-C.
An RNA fragment comprised of two guanosine, one uridine, one adenosine and three cytidine residues connected by 3'->5' phosphodiester linkages in the sequence G-U-G-A-C-C-C.
A pentapeptide comprising L-tryptophan, glycine, L-isoleucine, and two L-histidine residues coupled in sequence by peptide linkages.
An oligopeptide comprising L-tryptophan, L-tyrosine, glycine, L-tyrosine, and two L-histidine residues coupled in sequence by peptide linkages.
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-tryptophan in which the hydrogen at position 6 on the indole ring has been replaced by a chlorine.

An organic heterotetracyclic compound resulting from cyclocondensation of the 4- and 5-hydroxy groups of (2R,4S)-2-(4-methoxyphenyl)-6,8-dimethyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-chromene-4,5,7-triol across the 1- and 2-positions of beta-D-glucopyranose. It is a natural product extracted from the fern plant, Pronephrium penangianum and exerts antiproliferative and antifibrotic activity.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from O(3)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl]-L-serine.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group is specified as octanoyl.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from O(3)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl]-L-threonine.
An all-trans-retinyl ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of octanoic acid with the hydroxy group of all-trans-retinol.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from O(3)-{N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->6)]-alpha-D-mannosyl}-L-serine.
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-tryptophan in which the hydrogens at positions 6 and 7 on the indole ring have been replaced by chlorines.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from O(3)-{N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-[N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->6)]-alpha-D-mannosyl}-L-threonine.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group is specified as dodecanoyl.
An all-trans-retinyl ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of dodecanoic (lauric) acid with the hydroxy group of all-trans-retinol.
Any heparin oligosaccharide consisting of 12 glycosidically linked monosaccharide residues.
Any heparin oligosaccharide consisting of 14 glycosidically linked monosaccharide residues.
